<taxonomicName authority="Rodrigues and Junca, 2002" authorityName="Rodrigues and Junca" authorityYear="2002" box="[151,723,1421,1447]" class="Reptilia" family="Typhlopidae" genus="Typhlops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="amoipira">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,377,1421,1447]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Typhlops amoipira</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Rodrigues" box="[384,723,1421,1447]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refString="Rodrigues, M. T. &amp; Junca, F. A. (2002) Herpetofauna of the Quaternary sand dunes of the middle rio Sao Francisco, Bahia, Brazil. VII Typhlops amoipira sp. nov., a possible relative of Typhlops yonenage (Serpentes, Typhlopidae). Papeis Avulsos de Zoologia, 42, 325 - 333. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1590 / S 0031 - 10492002001300001" type="journal article" year="2002">
Rodrigues and Juncá, 
<number box="[664,723,1421,1447]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
“Cobra-cega”
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,904,1421,1483]" box="[151,370,1458,1483]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">(Figs. 8.6 and 21.3)</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1436,1533,1744]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Caatinga endemic species. Known from only two records, in the states of Bahia and Minas Gerais. It is distributed in areas with between 
<number box="[417,459,1570,1595]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="553.0">553</number>
and 
<quantity box="[521,596,1570,1595]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.29" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="m" value="629.0">629 m</quantity>
elevation. Inhabits bushy and herbaceous caatinga with bromeliads and clumps of grasses on sandy soils (
<bibRefCitation author="Rodrigues" box="[529,813,1607,1632]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refString="Rodrigues, M. T. &amp; Junca, F. A. (2002) Herpetofauna of the Quaternary sand dunes of the middle rio Sao Francisco, Bahia, Brazil. VII Typhlops amoipira sp. nov., a possible relative of Typhlops yonenage (Serpentes, Typhlopidae). Papeis Avulsos de Zoologia, 42, 325 - 333. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1590 / S 0031 - 10492002001300001" type="journal article" year="2002">
Rodrigues &amp; Juncá 
<number box="[753,813,1608,1632]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), along the São Francisco sandy dunes. It also occurs in cerrado 
<emphasis box="[245,389,1646,1669]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">sensu stricto</emphasis>
with sandy soils, dissected by veredas and riparian forests (Fernandes 
<emphasis box="[1219,1271,1645,1670]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number box="[1289,1350,1646,1670]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="2010.0">2010</number>
). It has fossorial and psammophylous habits, is nocturnal and diurnal, and feeds mostly on arthropods (
<bibRefCitation author="Rodrigues" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refString="Rodrigues, M. T. &amp; Junca, F. A. (2002) Herpetofauna of the Quaternary sand dunes of the middle rio Sao Francisco, Bahia, Brazil. VII Typhlops amoipira sp. nov., a possible relative of Typhlops yonenage (Serpentes, Typhlopidae). Papeis Avulsos de Zoologia, 42, 325 - 333. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1590 / S 0031 - 10492002001300001" type="journal article" year="2002">
Rodrigues &amp; Juncá 
<number box="[151,212,1720,1744]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
